  "notes": "Norman (Nouormand), an Oïl (Gallo-Romance) language. COMMITMENT: this map implements ONE variety and ONE norm — JÈRRIAIS (Jersey Norman) in its standard dictionary orthography. Norman is not one orthography: Guernésiais, Sercquiais, Cotentinais and the continental varieties each have their own spelling systems and assign different values to the same digraphs; they are OUT OF SCOPE here and would each merit their own spec. INPUT CONTRACT: lowercase Jèrriais text with its circumflexes and graves intact (â ê î ô û é è òe òê) — the accents carry vowel length and quality, so stripping them destroys the mapping. Distinctively Jèrriais: <th> = /ð/ (voiced) or /θ/, <ç> = /ʃ/, <tch> = /tʃ/, <dg> = /dʒ/, <ngn> = /ɲ/, <qu> = /k/, <ou> = /u/, <u> = /y/. Silent letters: <h> is usually mute (but /h/ in e.g. happer), <l> before <i>/<y> is mute (pliat), final <p> and infinitive/agentive <r> are mute. Five nasal vowels, each with a long counterpart written with a circumflex. Etymological French spelling means residual irregularity remains.",
